## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA support was removed from macOS**. `DSA.Create()` (and all DSA signing/verification operations) now **throws at runtime** on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify legacy signatures** (not create new ones), you have two options:

### Option A — Platform guard (minimal change)
If you must keep verifying existing DSA signatures, restrict that code path to Windows/Linux:

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification is not supported on macOS in .NET 11+.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
```

### Option B — Migrate to ECDSA/RSA (recommended long-term)
Re-sign or re-issue with a modern algorithm and update verification:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Recommendation

Since DSA is a legacy algorithm everywhere, **Option B** is preferred if you can re-sign the data. If you're stuck verifying signatures you can't re-issue, use **Option A** with the platform guard and run verification only on Linux/Windows CI agents.
